DOMAIN_OVERVIEW:
The temporal dimension of justice addresses how justice principles apply across time, including obligations between past, present, and future generations who may not coexist. This rapidly developing field encompasses several interconnected strands: (1) diachronic vs. synchronic justice - whether justice should be assessed at a single time-slice or across the entire course of lives/societies; (2) historical injustice and rectification - whether and how past wrongs generate present obligations, including the "supersession thesis" that changing circumstances can alter what justice requires; (3) intergenerational justice - what present generations owe to future (and past) people, complicated by the non-identity problem; (4) path dependency - how historical choices constrain present options and create temporal lock-in effects; (5) temporal priority principles - how to weight past occupancy versus current need versus future opportunity in allocating scarce located goods like housing and territory.

Key debates include: Waldron's supersession thesis (1992) versus critics arguing historical claims persist despite changed circumstances; Rawlsian time-slice principles versus historical entitlement theories (Nozick); person-affecting versus impersonal approaches to future generations; backward-looking (reparative) versus forward-looking (distributive) justice. Recent work (2015-2025) has applied these frameworks to climate justice, territorial rights, gentrification, indigenous land claims, and colonial reparations. The field has evolved from abstract philosophical puzzles to urgent practical applications, with significant empirical and normative integration.

RELEVANCE_TO_PROJECT:
This domain is CENTRAL to the housing justice research project. The core challenge - adjudicating between incumbent residents' claims based on past occupancy versus newcomers' claims based on present/future need - is precisely a temporal justice problem. The project requires principles for: (1) how to weight historical attachment and investment versus current housing need; (2) whether historical injustices (redlining, urban renewal, displacement) create persistent claims or can be superseded; (3) how path dependency constrains just housing allocation (e.g., neighborhoods shaped by past discrimination); (4) temporal framing of housing rights (moment-in-time vs. life-course vs. intergenerational). The supersession debate directly addresses whether gentrification-induced displacement wrongs can be rectified or are overtaken by changed circumstances. Occupancy rights theory provides conceptual tools for understanding place-based claims that accumulate over time.

RECENT_DEVELOPMENTS:
The field has seen explosive growth 2015-2025 with major monographs on territorial justice (Moore 2015, Stilz 2019, Nine 2022), intergenerational justice (Bidadanure 2021, Gosseries 2023, Truccone 2024), and climate justice (Caney's work 2014-2024). The supersession thesis has been comprehensively debated through Meyer & Waligore's 2022 special issue and 2023 book. Critical innovations include: Stilz's defense of occupancy rights independent of historical title; Bidadanure's integration of age-group justice with diachronic evaluation; Krishnamurthy & Moore's 2024 application to gentrification; Truccone's 2024 synthesis addressing post-colonial and climate injustices; growing attention to relational egalitarianism's temporal limits (Lippert-Rasmussen 2025). Empirical turn includes neuroscience of temporal discounting, behavioral economics of intertemporal choice, and climate science urgency.

NOTABLE_GAPS:
Limited direct application to urban housing allocation (Krishnamurthy & Moore 2024 is exception). Few works integrate temporal justice with located goods theory - most focus on fungible resources or abstract territory. Underdeveloped empirical operationalization of philosophical concepts like "reasons-responsiveness over time" or "occupancy rights thresholds." Little engagement with short-term rental markets, housing financialization, or demographic transitions. Insufficient attention to intersectionality - how temporal claims interact with race, class, and migration status over time. Need for more work on institutional design for temporal justice (beyond climate assemblies). Path dependency remains more descriptive (legal/economic) than normative (philosophical).

SYNTHESIS_GUIDANCE:
For the literature review, prioritize: (1) Waldron (1992) and Meyer & Waligore (2022) on supersession as conceptual foundation; (2) Goodin (2010) on temporal justice framework; (3) Gosseries (2023) and Thompson (2002) on intergenerational obligations; (4) Stilz (2013, 2019) and Moore (2015) on occupancy and territorial rights; (5) Krishnamurthy & Moore (2024) as direct application to gentrification. Key tension: backward-looking historical claims versus forward-looking distributive justice - housing project must navigate this. Distinguish pure historical entitlement (Nozick, problematic for displacement) from occupancy-based claims (Stilz, more promising) from pure distribution (Rawls, ignores attachment). Consider how path dependency creates moral constraints on distributive justice even if historical claims don't persist indefinitely.

KEY_POSITIONS:
- Historical supersession: 5 papers - Waldron's thesis that changed circumstances can supersede historical claims
- Anti-supersession/persistent claims: 4 papers - Meyer, Thompson, Butt arguing historical injustices create enduring obligations
- Intergenerational justice theories: 4 papers - Gosseries, Caney, Bidadanure on obligations across time
- Occupancy rights theory: 3 papers - Stilz, Moore, Nine on place-based temporal claims
- Temporal framing/diachronic justice: 3 papers - Goodin, Truccone on how time affects justice assessment
- Applications (climate, territory, gentrification): 2 papers - Recent applied work
