  note = {CORE ARGUMENT: Comprehensive examination of temporal dimension in justice theory. Core question: should historical injustices always be repaired? Argues that circumstances change over time affecting justice (supersession), but repairing historical injustices can and must be reconciled with distributive justice imperatives. Examines supersession thesis in two contexts: post-colonial injustices against Latin American indigenous peoples and climate burden distribution. Four aspects of historical injustice: (1) temporal dimension of justice itself, (2) connection between current claimants/duty-bearers and original victims/perpetrators, (3) how changed circumstances affect justice requirements, (4) appropriate forms of reparation. Defends reconciliation of reparative and distributive justice rather than choosing between them. RELEVANCE: Sophisticated synthesis directly applicable to housing justice temporal dilemmas. Housing faces exactly Truccone's core tension: reconciling backward-looking claims (displaced residents deserve rectification) with forward-looking distributive justice (newcomers need affordable housing). Truccone's four-aspect framework structures analysis: (1) How does time itself affect housing justice assessment? (2) What connections link current actors to past displacement? (3) When do changed circumstances (neighborhood transformation, demographic shifts) alter justice requirements? (4) What forms of housing reparation are appropriate (return, compensation, priority access)? Critical insight: don't simply choose reparative vs. distributive - integrate both. The project needs principles for this integration in housing context. POSITION: Temporal justice requires reconciling, not choosing between, reparative (backward-looking) and distributive (forward-looking) justice.},
  keywords = {temporal-justice, historical-injustice, supersession, reparative-justice, distributive-justice, High}
